data.title: Study proposal
data.definition: Defining outlines for a new study/data collection, including needs for information and general  research  objectives, as well  as main concepts, study scope and methodology, usually to be presented for approval to funders, partners, or other relevant bodies.

data.title: Funding
data.definition: Decisions to extend financial support for the study/data collection.

data.title: Study design
data.definition: Detailed planning for carrying out the study/data collection: refining concepts and identifying ways to measure them, defining the target population, time dimension, sampling frame and sample selection, data collection methodology, production systems and workflows, etc.

data.title: Instrument design
data.definition: Building the data collection instrument, for example, the questionnaire or interview questions, focus group topics, observation forms for an observational design, standardized record review, independent and dependent variables for an experimental design, etc.

data.title: Questionnaire translation
data.definition: Translating the source questionnaire into other languages, for example, in cross-national surveys or in national surveys conducted in multilingual countries.

data.title: Questionnaire adaptation
data.definition: Changing the wording of questions to reflect cultural or institutional differences if same-language questionnaires are administered in different regions or countries.

data.title: Interviewer training
data.definition: Training the interviewers that administer questionnaires in survey-type studies.

data.title: Ethics review
data.definition: Review of the study/data collection to ensure that it complies with statutory ethics requirements or regulations, including verification of the informed consent statement, performed by a qualified body, like a Research Ethics Committee, or Institutional Review Board.

data.title: Legal review
data.definition: Review of the study/data collection in terms of compliance with the law  (legislation concerning confidentiality, the protection of children, etc.).

data.title: Sampling
data.definition: Selecting the sample for the study/data collection.

data.title: Instrument pre-testing
data.definition: Small-scale application of the data collection instrument designed to identify potential problems before using it for the entire study.

data.title: Pilot study
data.definition: Dress rehearsal of the full project, for example, by administering the questionnaire to a small number of people, then coding and analyzing results, etc.

data.title: Data collection
data.definition: Setting up, running and finalizing the data collection process, including follow-up procedures, etc.

data.title: Data collection reports
data.definition: Reports on designing and conducting the data collection process, including methodological decisions and problems encountered. These may take the form of conference posters or presentations, journal articles or online publications, book chapters, etc.

data.title: Data processing
data.definition: Changes, additions or deletions brought to the data at any point in time after collection.

data.title: Data processing: Coding
data.definition: Converting raw data into machine-readable codes.

data.title: Data processing: Classification
data.definition: Documenting the meaning/substance of coded data.

data.title: Data processing: Transcriptions of interviews
data.definition: Transferring video- or audio-taped data into written form.

data.title: Data processing: Weighting
data.definition: Calculating weight variables and adding them to the data.

data.title: Data processing: Aggregation
data.definition: Calculating cumulative measures of individual-level data or microdata.

data.title: Data processing: Composite measures
data.definition: Calculating scales, indexes, or typologies and adding them to the data.

data.title: Data processing: Derivation
data.definition: Calculating new variables from measured variables, usually by recodes.

data.title: Data processing: Quality checks
data.definition: Checks for consistency, undocumented codes, missing data representation, etc.

data.title: Data processing: Data integration
data.definition: Creating complex datasets by merging related data, for example, hierarchical datasets with multiple but related  analysis units, or multiple-wave datasets, or data collected in different countries for a cross-national study, etc.

data.title: Data processing: Disclosure limitation
data.definition: Editing the data to prevent identification of subjects, for example, performing anonymization measures like recoding or top-coding sensitive variables like income levels, suppressing some geographic indicators, or replacing personal names with pseudonyms and/or categorizing background or demographic information in qualitative data.

data.title: Data processing: Imputation
data.definition: Replacing missing data points with values calculated according to an imputation technique.

data.title: Metadata production
data.definition: Documenting the data, for example, by producing study-level and variable descriptions.

data.title: Metadata editing
data.definition: Amending the metadata to reflect changes in the data or to improve or enhance documentation.

data.title: Metadata translation
data.definition: Translating the metadata into another language.

data.title: Final report
data.definition: Complete account on how the study was conducted through all its stages, often required by funders or other administrative bodies.

data.title: Evaluation
data.definition: Analysis of how the study, in all its stages, was managed and/or conducted, including the outcome of methodological, technical, and business decisions. May serve as a basis for changes or improvements in planning future iterations of the data collection, or entirely new projects.

data.title: Original release
data.definition: First release of data and/or metadata to other individuals and/or agencies than the study producers.

data.title: Deposit
data.definition: Handing over the data and available metadata (Submission Information Package in OAIS terms) to a data archive or repository for preservation, possible further processing,  and dissemination.

data.title: Preservation package production
data.definition: Producing a preservation package of the data for archiving purposes (Archival Information Package in OAIS terms).

data.title: Dissemination package production
data.definition: Producing a dissemination package for distribution of the data (Dissemination Information Package in OAIS terms).

data.title: Dissemination package release
data.definition: Publishing or otherwise making the dissemination package available to users.

data.title: Data analysis reports
data.definition: Reports describing how the data were analyzed,  as well as the resulting findings. These may take the form of conference posters or presentations, journal articles or online publications, books, book chapters, etc.

data.title: New version release
data.definition: Publishing or otherwise making a new version of the data and/or metadata available to users.

data.title: Decimal
data.definition: A subset of real numbers, which can be represented by a finite-length sequence of decimal digits (0-9) separated by a period as a decimal indicator. An optional leading sign is allowed. If the sign is omitted, "+" is assumed. Leading and trailing zeroes are optional. If the fractional part is zero, the period and following zero(es) can be omitted. For example: -1.23, 12678967.543233, +100000.00, 210.

data.title: Float
data.definition: Single-precision 32-bit floating point type: The basic value space of float consists of the values m*2^e, where m is an integer whose absolute value is less than 2^24, and e is an integer between -149 and 104, inclusive. In addition, it also contains the following three special values: positive and negative infinity and not-a-number (NaN). The special values positive and negative infinity and not-a-number have lexical representations INF, -INF and NaN, respectively. Lexical representations for zero may take a positive or negative sign. For example, -1E4, 1267.43233E12, 12.78e-2, 12 , -0, 0 and INF are all legal literals for float.

data.title: Double
data.definition: Double-precision 64-bit floating point type. The basic value space of double consists of the values m*2^e, where m is an integer whose absolute value is less than 2^53, and e is an integer between -1075 and 970, inclusive. In addition to the basic value space described above, the value space of double also contains the following three special values: positive and negative infinity and not-a-number (NaN). The special values positive and negative infinity and not-a-number have lexical representations INF, -INF and NaN, respectively. Lexical representations for zero may take a positive or negative sign. For example, -1E4, 1267.43233E12, 12.78e-2, 12 , -0, 0 and INF are all legal literals for double.

data.title: Duration
data.definition: A duration of time. The value space of "duration" is a six-dimensional space in which the coordinates designate the Gregorian year, month, day, hour, minute, and second components as defined in ISO 8601. These components are ordered in their significance by their order of appearance as year, month, day, hour, minute, and second. The lexical representation of duration is the extended format PnYnMnDTnHnMnS, where P is the flag for duration (i.e., Period) and is constant, nY represents the number of years, nM the number of months, nD the number of days, T is the date/time separator, nH the number of hours, nM the number of minutes and nS the number of seconds. The number of seconds can include decimal digits to arbitrary precision. For example, to indicate a duration of 1 year, 2 months, 3 days, 10 hours, and 30 minutes, one would write: "P1Y2M3DT10H30M." An optional preceding minus sign ("-") is allowed, to indicate a negative duration: a duration of minus 120 days would be indicated as: "-P120D" (from: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/#duration).

data.title: hexBinary
data.definition: Even-lengthed sequence of hexadecimal digits representing an N times 8-bit integer.

data.title: base64Binary
data.definition: Sequence of multiples of four base64 digits, where each 4-tuple represents a 24-bit integer. Each digit (a-z, A-Z, 0-9, +, /) represents a 6-bit integer between 0 and 63.

data.title: Single translation
data.definition: A single translator produces one translation. Use this broader term if the translator makes the decisions about the final version, if it is not known who makes the final decisions, or if the review process is not explained in either of the narrower terms.

data.title: Single translation: Individual review
data.definition: A single translator produces one translation. Another individual reviews the translation, possibly in consultation with the translator. There may be more than one review round and different individual reviewers in each round.  An  adjudicator (possibly a reviewer) approves the final version.

data.title: Single translation: Committee review
data.definition: A single translator produces one translation. A committee, possibly including the translator, reviews it and approves the final version. There may be more than one review round. In survey translation, the committee may include survey, domain and language experts.

data.title: Split translation
data.definition: Two or more translators produce one translation by splitting up a source text (for example, a questionnaire) into subsections and each translating a subsection. Use this broader term if the translators decide on the final version amongst themselves, if it is not known who makes the final decisions or if the review process is not explained in either of the narrower terms.

data.title: Split translation: Individual review
data.definition: Two or more translators produce one translation by splitting up a source text (for example, a questionnaire) into subsections and each translating a subsection. An individual reviews the whole translation, possibly in consultation with the translators. There may be more than one review round and different individual reviewers in each round. An adjudicator (possibly a reviewer) approves the final version.

data.title: Split translation: Committee review
data.definition: Two or more translators produce one translation by splitting up a source text (for example, a questionnaire) into subsections and each translating a subsection. A committee, possibly including the translators, reviews the whole translation and approves the final version. There may be more than one review round. In survey translation, the committee may include survey, domain and language experts.

data.title: Parallel translations
data.definition: Two or more translators each produce a separate,  independent  translation of a whole text. Use this broader term if the  translators decide on a final version amongst themselves, if it is not known who makes the final decisions or if the review process is not described in either of the narrower terms.

data.title: Parallel translations: Individual review
data.definition: Two or more translators each produce a separate,  independent  translation of a whole text. An individual reviews all the translations and makes decisions on the final version, possibly in consultation with the translators. There may be more than one review round and different individual reviewers in each round. An adjudicator (possibly a reviewer) approves the final version.

data.title: Parallel translations: Committee review
data.definition: Two or more translators each produce a separate, independent  translation of a whole text. A committee, possibly including the translators, reviews all the translations, and makes decisions on the final version. There may be more than one review round. In survey translation, the committee may include survey, domain and language experts.

data.title: Same language adaptation
data.definition: A country or region uses the final translation of another country or region sharing the same language as the basis for their own translation. Some of the content of the original translation is modified to reflect linguistic, cultural, socio-economic or political differences. If needed, this term may be used alongside other relevant terms from this list.

data.title: Same language harmonization
data.definition: Two or more countries or regions sharing the same language cooperate in the translation process, producing a commonly agreed translation which each country or region can then modify to account for linguistic, cultural, socio-economic or political differences. If needed, this term may be used alongside other relevant terms from this list.

data.title: Translation method unspecified
data.definition: It is not known what kind of translation method has been used.

data.title: Other
data.definition: The translation method is known but not in the list. If needed, use the free-text element for a more extensive description.

data.title: Numeric
data.definition: Data consisting largely of values expressed as digits from 0 to 9 and, optionally, signs for negative values, decimal points, or letters only when intended to represent numbers (for example, A-F or a-f in hexadecimal).

data.title: Text
data.definition: Data consisting largely of text, including letters, numbers, and special characters or symbols used in writing for punctuation, abbreviation, etc. For example, interview transcriptions, narratives or essays written by study participants, newspaper articles, etc.

data.title: Still image
data.definition: Static images, such as graphs, drawings, photographs, diagnostic/medical images like X-rays, etc.

data.title: Geospatial
data.definition: Geospatial data are any type of data with spatial coordinates that allow them to be mapped to the Earth's surface. They can represent physical objects, discrete areas or continuous surfaces. Discrete geospatial data are usually represented using vector data consisting of points, lines and polygons, while continuous geospatial data are usually represented by raster data, consisting of a grid of cells that each has its own value. Any number of applications in a wide range of areas produce geospatial data, such as GIS, Remote Sensing equipment, GPS units, archaeological total stations, manual mapping and computer-aided design (CAD), in a number of formats, including images, vector, text, and tabular data. Vector-based geospatial data include tables listing archaeological sites along with their coordinates, text-based files (e.g. XML) containing coordinates and topology for historic road networks, voting figures for political parties by administrative area. Raster-based geospatial data include satellite images, aerial photographs, scanned maps, and digital maps of elevations, vegetation, land-use, sea surface temperatures, air pollution, soil-types, etc.

data.title: Audio
data.definition: Recorded sound, including voice, music, etc.

data.title: Video
data.definition: Moving images. May include films, animation, digital recordings, visual output from simulations, recorded television programs, etc. May be mute or may include synchronized sound.

data.title: Software
data.definition: Computer program(s) in source code (human-readable) or compiled form.

data.title: Interactive resource
data.definition: A resource requiring interaction from the user to be understood, executed, or experienced. For example, training modules, query/response portals, files that require action from the user, etc.

data.title: 3D
data.definition: Virtual three-dimensional representations of objects, architecture, places, etc.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use when the kind of data format is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: DateTime
data.definition: Used to specify a date and time in the form "year, month, day, hour, minutes and seconds" (YYYY-MM-DD hh:mm:ss). In a DateTime string expression, the time portion is preceded by a "T", for example, 2018-02-22T13:00:00. A time zone specification may be included either by entering the UTC date and time followed by a "Z", or by adding a positive or negative time after the stated time to indicate the offset from UTC time. For example, 1 pm U.S. Eastern Standard Time may be expressed as 2018-02-22T18:00:00Z, or as 2018-02-22T13:00:00-5:00.

data.title: Time
data.definition: Used to specify a time in the form "hour, minutes and seconds" (hh:mm:ss). A time zone specification may be included either by entering the UTC time followed by a "Z", or by adding a positive or negative time after the stated time to indicate the offset from UTC time. For example, 1 pm U.S. Eastern Standard Time may be expressed as 18:00:00Z, or as 13:00:00-5:00.

data.title: Date
data.definition: Used to specify a date in the form "year, month, day" (YYYY-MM-DD). A time zone specification may be included either by entering a UTC date followed by a "Z" or by adding a positive or negative time after the stated date to indicate the offset from UTC time. For example, February 20th, 2018 in Eastern Australia could be expressed as 2018-02-19Z, or as 2018-02-20+10:00.

data.title: YearMonth
data.definition: Defines a part of a date - the year and month (YYYY-MM).

data.title: Year
data.definition: Defines a part of a date - the year (YYYY).

data.title: MonthDay
data.definition: Defines a part of a date - the month and day (MM-DD).

data.title: Day
data.definition: Defines a part of a date - the day (DD).

data.title: Month
data.definition: Defines a part of a date - the month (MM).

data.title: Duration
data.definition: Used to specify a time period or interval in the form "number of years, number of months, number of days, number of hours, number of minutes, and number of seconds, preceded by a "P" (PnYnMnDTnHnMnS). The letter "T" indicates the start of the time section. For example, P5Y2M10DT15H stands for a period of five years, two months, 10 days, and 15 hours. A period preceded by the minus sign ("-") will indicate a negative duration, for example, -P10D stands for a period of minus 10 days.

data.title: Timespan
data.definition: The TimeSpan structure represents a length of time (duration of time or elapsed time), and may be expressed as start/end, start/duration, or duration/end. Start, end, and duration are documented using the designated DateTime structures. Examples: start/end 2018-02-22T13:00:00/2018-02-22T14:30:00; start/duration 2018-02-Approved: The TimeSpan structure represents a length of time (duration of time or elapsed time), and may be expressed as start/end, start/duration, or duration/end. Start, end, and duration are documented using the designated DateTime structures. Examples: start/end 2018-02-22T13:00:00/2018-02-22T14:30:00; start/duration 2018-02-22T13:00:00/1H30M; duration/end 1H20M/2018-02-22T14:30:00. For start/end expressions, if any element is missing from the end value, it is assumed to be the same as for the start value, including the time zone if used. For example, a two-hour meeting on 14 Dec 2007 can be represented as 2007-12-14T13:30:00/15:30:00, or 2007-12-14T13:30:00/2H.

data.title: Administrative
data.definition: A concept group created for administrative purposes, for instance for subsetting or reorganizing data.

data.title: Thematic
data.definition: A concept group created to bring together concepts reflecting the same general theme, or topic; for example, a group called "Trust" can include trust in institutions, trust in government, as well as interpersonal trust.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use when the type of concept group is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: Identical
data.definition: Use when the compared items have identical content. For variables, for example, all the elements of a variable description (name, label, question text, category values and codes, universe, concept) will be identical in form.

data.title: Some
data.definition: Use when the compared items have similar but not identical content. For variables, for example, some of the elements of a variable description (name, label, question text, category values and codes, universe, concept) will be identical in form, while others will be different.

data.title: None
data.definition: Normally not used, as it would not be expected to compare items that have nothing in common. This term was necessary to complete the commonality range, and may be used in special cases, as determined by user needs (for instance, when comparability was expected, but not found).

data.title: Project/Study design
data.definition: Describing the rationale, and putting together a specific plan for conducting a study or research project.

data.title: Project/Study design: Conceptualization
data.definition: Developing high-level research concepts as well as specific concepts to be measured. Conceptualization involves clarifying the concepts with verbal definitions and examples as well as expressing relationships among the concepts.

data.title: Project/Study design: Instrument design
data.definition: Conceiving and planning for the data collection instrument(s). May include the operationalization of concepts into questions and indicators, instrument testing, forward translation and subsequent changes in the master instrument(s),  as well as designing  and testing other types of data collection instruments than survey questionnaires.

data.title: Project/Study design: Methodology development
data.definition: Developing guidelines or protocols for the methods used to conduct the study, and to process and analyze the data. For example, directions and instructions for collecting data, conducting interviews, translating questionnaires, input harmonization, using weights, etc.

data.title: Project/Study design: Weights design
data.definition: Developing weights to assist in adjusting the data to the desired objectives of the study, for example, to make the data representative of the target population.

data.title: Project/Study design: Standards development
data.definition: Developing models for the structure and distribution of data and metadata in fixed, predictable formats. For example, the DATS (Data Tag Suite) for describing biomedical data, the Data Documentation Initiative (DDI) for describing social, behavioral, economic, and health sciences data, etc.

data.title: Project/Study design: Data modeling
data.definition: Creating a data model based on an analysis of data objects and their relationships, data properties, as well as data flows and processes. It is often the first step in database creation, tool and standards development, etc., and typically involves a progression from a conceptual model to a logical model, and then to a physical schema.

data.title: Project/Study design: Sampling design
data.definition: Defining which elements of the target population are included in the sample, as well as the rules and procedures by which they will be selected.

data.title: Data management
data.definition: Development and execution of architectures, policies, practices and procedures to handle data at any stage of its life cycle. Includes processes and activities related to the selection, organization and integration of data, their annotation, as well as their publication and preservation so that the data maintain their value over time, and remain available for reuse.

data.title: Ethics review
data.definition: Reviewing whether a research proposal or study complies with ethical principles based on legislation or approved ethical guidelines (soft legislation).

data.title: Data collection
data.definition: Activities relating to the process of gathering data in an established, systematic fashion that enables answering the stated research questions, testing hypotheses, and evaluating outcomes. Maps to 'DataCollector' in DataCite.

data.title: Sample selection
data.definition: Selecting units from the target population.

data.title: Data entry
data.definition: Entering or updating data into a computer system, often from other forms of media, like paper questionnaires, newspaper articles, etc.

data.title: Data processing
data.definition: Performing operations that result in changes to the data, including data cleaning, editing, post-harmonization, etc. Maps to 'DataCurator' in DataCite.

data.title: Data processing: Disclosure control
data.definition: Planning or using specific techniques to preserve the anonymity of individual or other entities that the data refer to. For example, anonymization, pseudonymization, or removal of direct and indirect identifiers.

data.title: Data processing: Data aggregation
data.definition: Producing individually collected data in a summary form, for purposes such as statistical analysis. A common aggregation goal is to obtain more information about particular population groups, based on specific variables, such as age, profession, education, or income.

data.title: Data processing: Data integration
data.definition: Combining data from separate sources into meaningful information. For example, linking register data with survey data or integrating datasets collected in different countries into a cross-national dataset.

data.title: Data processing: Data validation
data.definition: The process of checking data to ensure that all of them have acceptable values, that they are accurate, coherent, consistent, complete and in the expected format.

data.title: Data acquisition
data.definition: Acquiring data and supporting documentation from potential contributors for further preservation and/or dissemination.

data.title: Metadata production
data.definition: Generating data documentation. For example, a study description covering study rationale, methodology, and other characteristics of the dataset as a whole; variable-level documentation (labels, frequencies, question text); references to study-related materials or publications, etc.

data.title: Data distribution
data.definition: Distributing/disseminating the data to users and making them available for reuse. Maps to 'Distributor' in DataCite.

data.title: Data hosting
data.definition: Housing, servicing, and maintaining data and, usually, the accompanying  metadata or related documentation. Maps to to 'HostingInstitution' in DataCite.

data.title: Long-term preservation/archiving
data.definition: Protecting and maintaining the integrity and usability of data and accompanying metadata so that they remain available to future generations. Maps to 'DataManager' in DataCite.

data.title: Consulting
data.definition: Providing expert advice.

data.title: Contact
data.definition: Individual, or organization that may be reached to obtain data-related information. Maps to  'ContactPerson' in DataCite.

data.title: Data analysis
data.definition: The process of investigating the data to help answer research questions and reach conclusions.

data.title: Editing
data.definition: Arranging, revising, and preparing materials (e.g., text, audio or video) for final production or publication. Maps to 'Editor' in DataCite.

data.title: Equipment development
data.definition: Creating and maintaining equipment needed at any stage of the data life cycle.

data.title: Evaluation
data.definition: Assessing quality, worth and significance. Includes, for example, establishing evaluation criteria, gathering evaluation inputs and conducting the process of evaluation.

data.title: Funding provision
data.definition: Providing financial support to a program or project, usually by an organization or government. Funding is made for a specific purpose for which the successful applicant must often account in full.

data.title: Funding/sponsorship acquisition
data.definition: Searching for, and/or obtaining financial or other type of support for a program or project.

data.title: Sponsorship
data.definition: Providing support for research or for other work or activities. Includes in-kind support, for example, providing staff time, facilities or instrumentation. Maps to 'Sponsor' in DataCite.

data.title: Graphic design
data.definition: Combining text and images to support and enhance content, and make it visually appealing and user-friendly.

data.title: Project operations
data.definition: Initiating, planning, executing, controlling, and closing the work of a team designed to achieve specific goals.

data.title: Project operations: Project leader
data.definition: Person officially designated as head of a project, or subproject team that carries out the work for developing a resource. The project leader remains closely involved in the work performed throughout the life of the project. Maps to 'ProjectLeader' in DataCite.

data.title: Project operations: Project manager
data.definition: Person officially designated as manager of a project. This function normally has more administrative responsibilities than actual work involvement. Maps to 'ProjectManager' in DataCite.

data.title: Project operations: Project member
data.definition: Person that contributes and participates as a member in a designated project or project team. Maps to 'ProjectMember' in DataCite.

data.title: Promotion
data.definition: Raising awareness and understanding of products and services, to attract potential users.

data.title: Registration authority
data.definition: A standards-setting body from which Registration Agencies obtain official recognition and guidance. For example, the International DOI Foundation (IDF) serves as the registration authority for the International Standards Organization (ISO) in the area/domain of Digital Object Identifiers.

data.title: Researcher
data.definition: An individual involved in analyzing the data or the study results, but whose role is to help with the research rather than be a creator.  For example, a researcher may seek, and find additional data from another source and correlate it to the study or experiment that is being conducted. Maps to 'Researcher' in DataCite.

data.title: Research group
data.definition: Group of individuals involved in the research. Maps to 'ResearchGroup' in DataCite.

data.title: Rights holding
data.definition: Owning property rights, including intellectual property rights over the resource. Maps to 'RightsHolder' in DataCite.

data.title: Rights management
data.definition: Managing licenses for distributed data, tools, and other research materials on behalf of the rights holder.

data.title: Software development
data.definition: Creating and maintaining software needed at any stage of the data life cycle.

data.title: Supervision
data.definition: Overseeing one or more individuals or teams in their work. Maps to 'Supervisor' in DataCite.

data.title: Training
data.definition: Imparting information and/or instructions to improve the recipient's performance or to help attain a required level of knowledge or skills related to research or research data. For example, training interviewers, translators, data archivists, or data analysts.

data.title: Translation
data.definition: Expressing the content of text or speech in a different language than the original language used. For example, questionnaire or study report translation.

data.title: User support
data.definition: Providing assistance to users of data, metadata, tools, etc.

data.title: Visualization
data.definition: Representing data, analysis results, or other information as a chart, image or animation, to aid in the understanding of their meaning.

data.title: Website development
data.definition: Creating and maintaining a website related to the data. May include web design, building a user interface, network security configuration, etc.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use if the role is known but not in the list. Can be mapped to the roles 'RelatedPerson', 'Producer', and 'Work Package Leader' in DataCite.

data.title: Arithmetic mean
data.definition: Mathematical average of a set of values. The mean is calculated by adding up two or more values and dividing the total by their number. In social/political science, it is usually the sum of the measurements divided by the number of subjects, or cases.

data.title: Geometric mean
data.definition: Average value of all data if extracting the nth root of the product of all (n) values. Rarely used in social sciences.

data.title: Harmonic mean
data.definition: Average value of all data if calculating the reciprocal of the arithmetic mean of the reciprocal of values. Rarely used in social sciences.

data.title: Trimmed mean
data.definition: The (arithmetic) mean calculated after discarding given parts of observations at the high and low end (e.g., interquartile mean when the lowest 25% and the highest 25% are discarded, and the mean of the remaining values is calculated).

data.title: Standard error of the mean
data.definition: Provides an estimate of how much the sample mean differs from the actual mean of the population.

data.title: Mode
data.definition: The most frequently observed data value (Statistics Canada).

data.title: Median
data.definition: The middle value in a set of values arranged in ascending order. Half of the values fall below the median, and half above it. If the set has an even number of values, the median will be the average of the two middle ones.

data.title: Valid cases
data.definition: Cases with observations which are considered to be valid, i.e., providing substantial information and to be included for calculation.

data.title: Invalid cases
data.definition: Cases which are considered/defined as "missing" (e.g., not ascertained, not applicable, etc.), usually excluded from calculation.

data.title: Minimum
data.definition: The lowest valid value in a variable.

data.title: Maximum
data.definition: The highest valid value in a variable.

data.title: Range
data.definition: The range of valid values, i.e., all values that fall between the lowest and highest valid values.

data.title: Sum
data.definition: The sum or total of the values, across all valid cases.

data.title: Variance
data.definition: The variance is the mean square deviation of the variable around the average value. It reflects the dispersion of a frequency distribution around its mean (OECD Glossary of Statistics).

data.title: Standard deviation
data.definition: Indicates the degree to which individuals within the sample differ from the sample mean.

data.title: Coefficient of variation
data.definition: Standard deviation divided by the mean.

data.title: Average absolute deviation
data.definition: The average of the absolute differences between each value and the overall mean. Measure of statistical dispersion around the mean, alternative to Standard Deviation.

data.title: Median absolute deviation
data.definition: The median absolute deviation from the median. Measure of statistical dispersion around the median.

data.title: First quartile
data.definition: The first of three values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into four equal parts.

data.title: Second quartile
data.definition: The second of three values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into four equal parts (= median).

data.title: Third quartile
data.definition: The third of three values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into four equal parts.

data.title: Interquartile range
data.definition: The range between the first and third quartile values.

data.title: First quintile
data.definition: The first of four values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into five equal parts.

data.title: Second quintile
data.definition: The second of four values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into five equal parts.

data.title: Third quintile
data.definition: The third of four values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into five equal parts.

data.title: Fourth quintile
data.definition: The fourth of four values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into five equal parts.

data.title: Interquintile range
data.definition: The range between the first and fourth quintile values.

data.title: First decile
data.definition: The first of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Second decile
data.definition: The second of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Third decile
data.definition: The third of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Fourth decile
data.definition: The fourth of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Fifth decile
data.definition: The fifth of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts (= median).

data.title: Sixth decile
data.definition: The sixth of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Seventh decile
data.definition: The seventh of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Eighth decile
data.definition: The eighth of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Ninth decile
data.definition: The ninth of nine values which separate the total frequency of a distribution into ten equal parts.

data.title: Interdecile range
data.definition: The range between the first and ninth decile values.

data.title: Other percentile
data.definition: A percentile not covered by any of the other percentile terms.

data.title: Skewness
data.definition: A measure for the asymmetry of a probability distribution of a variable.

data.title: Kurtosis
data.definition: A measure for the "peakedness" of a probability distribution of a variable.

data.title: Shapiro-Wilk
data.definition: Normality test statistics.

data.title: Percentage of valid cases
data.definition: Indicates the percentage of valid cases of the total number of cases.

data.title: Percentage of invalid cases
data.definition: Indicates the percentage of invalid cases of the total number of cases.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use if the summary statistic type is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts
data.definition: Official, formal, or semi-formal documents listing for example items, names, occurrences, actions, or results, and preserved in writing or some other permanent form for later reference.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Administrative
data.definition: Information collected on individuals or groups as part of the routine administrative procedures of an agency, business, or institution. Such data are not usually collected with research purposes in mind, may be voluminous, and may require preparation such as coding in order to be usable by researchers. Examples: income tax forms, population registers, naturalization records, birth/death certificates, patent applications, etc.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Historical
data.definition: Historical records preserve information and constitute evidence about past events. They may be produced by individuals, groups, or organizations. Administrative records become historical when they are no longer retained, or actively used by the issuing agency for their original purpose. Examples include parish registers, estate records, wills, chronicles, etc.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Legal
data.definition: Records pertaining to law and its administration, for example records related to cases that have been brought to court or to a tribunal.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Medical/Clinical
data.definition: Health-related data created or collected by health care professionals about a patient. Usually include the results of medical tests or measurements, findings from consultations or clinical trial programs, etc.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Academic/Aptitude
data.definition: Information gathered during an evaluation process and presented as results. Examples include educational tests, IQ tests, verbal or logical reasoning tests, competence tests for professional occupations, etc.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Economic/Financial
data.definition: Records of the financial activities of a business, person, state institution or other organizations or entities. Examples are statements of retained earnings, cash flow, income statements, a company's balance sheet and tax return.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Personal
data.definition: Records or accounts created unofficially by individuals or families for other purposes than research. Examples may include private diaries or memoirs, family record books or Bibles, collections of personal documents, photographs, etc.

data.title: Registers/Records/Accounts: Voting results
data.definition: Details of votes cast for candidates in an election (also known as 'election returns/results'), parliamentary or organizational votes on policies, motions or proposals, public referendums, etc.

data.title: Events/Interactions
data.definition: Events are usually one-time, individual occurrences, with a limited or short duration. An event may be listed as data source when it is directly observed or recorded for research. Interactions are events in which two or more people, groups, objects or systems act upon one another having reciprocal influence, or effect. Examples: types of gatherings (ceremonies, competitions, festivals, meetings), riots, terrorist attacks, computing events (i.e., actions or occurrences detected by computer programs), etc.

data.title: Processes
data.definition: Processes are sequences of occurrences, events, activities, actions or operations that take place over time and bring about changes or transformations in organisms, objects, ideas or social phenomena. For example, a business process may include receiving orders, invoicing, shipping the products, or setting a marketing budget.

data.title: Processes: Workflow(s)
data.definition: Sequence of steps and processes through which a piece of work passes from initiation to completion (adapted from the Oxford dictionary online: http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/us/definition/american_english/workflow). Examples from data life cycle: data collection, data processing, data analysis, data archiving, etc.

data.title: Communications
data.definition: Messages resulting from the act or process of using words, sounds, signs, or behaviors to convey or exchange information, ideas, thoughts, feelings, etc. (adapted from www.merriam-webster.com).

data.title: Communications: Public
data.definition: Communications addressed directly to a public audience, for example, in person (public gatherings, political rallies, etc.), by means of broadcast, print or Internet mass media (radio, television, print or online newspapers/journals), by means of billboards, banners or other signage placed in public view, or social media (public postings on Facebook, Twitter, and others).

data.title: Communications: Interpersonal
data.definition: Communications made by an individual to another individual or a private group of persons, for purposes other than research. For example emails, letters, telephone conversations, social media postings with limited access.

data.title: Research data
data.definition: Pre-existing data; data that have already been collected and/or used for a different research project.

data.title: Research data: Published
data.definition: Pre-existing data that have been made available to the general public, or sections thereof.

data.title: Research data: Unpublished
data.definition: Pre-existing data that have not been made available to the general public, or sections thereof.

data.title: Population group
data.definition: Group of individuals that can be defined by one or several common characteristics: ethnicity, race, gender, age range, geographic location or distribution, level of education, income level or economic status, professional status, state of health or medical conditions, or belonging to specific communities (e.g., special interest groups, or social media), or networks, etc.

data.title: Geographic area
data.definition: An area of the Earth, demarcated for the purposes of administration, politics, environment, etc. The demarcation is identifiable via coordinates or other systems used to identify position precisely.

data.title: Physical objects
data.definition: Natural or man-made entities with spatial locations. For instance, works of art, constructions, rock samples, machines, etc. These are considered data sources if the data describe the physical characteristics of the given object rather than any information encoded in it.

data.title: Biological samples
data.definition: Biological materials collected from living organisms, including, for example, biological specimens of human or animal organs, cells or tissues such as hair, muscle or tumor tissue, bodily fluids such as blood, urine, saliva, extracted material such as DNA and RNA, microorganisms, plant matter, etc. The source of the data are the samples themselves, not measurements and/or other tests applied to them.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use when the data source is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: Integer
data.definition: Whole numbers,  the infinite set of integers, no minimum or maximum value.  An integer datatype corresponding to the W3C XML Schema's xs:integer datatype.

data.title: Int
data.definition: Whole numbers in the range -2147483648 .. 2147483647. An integer datatype corresponding to the W3C XML Schema's xs:int datatype.

data.title: Long
data.definition: Whole numbers in the range -9223372036854775808 .. 9223372036854775807. A numeric datatype corresponding to the W3C XML Schema's xs:long datatype.

data.title: Short
data.definition: Whole numbers in the range -32768 .. 32767. A numeric datatype corresponding to the W3C XML Schema's xs:short datatype.

data.title: Decimal
data.definition: A subset of real numbers, which can be represented by a finite-length sequence of decimal digits (0-9) separated by a period as a decimal indicator. An optional leading sign is allowed. If the sign is omitted, "+" is assumed. Leading and trailing zeroes are optional. If the fractional part is zero, the period and following zero(es) can be omitted. For example: -1.23, 12678967.543233, +100000.00, 210. A numeric datatype corresponding to the W3C XML Schema's xs:decimal datatype.

data.title: Float
data.definition: Single-precision 32-bit floating point type: The basic value space of float consists of the values m*2^e, where m is an integer whose absolute value is less than 2^24, and e is an integer between -149 and 104, inclusive. In addition, it also contains the following three special values: positive and negative infinity and not-a-number (NaN). The special values positive and negative infinity and not-a-number have lexical representations INF, -INF and NaN, respectively. Lexical representations for zero may take a positive or negative sign. For example, -1E4, 1267.43233E12, 12.78e-2, 12 , -0, 0 and INF are all legal literals for float. A numeric datatype corresponding to the W3C XML Schema's xs:float datatype.

data.title: Double
data.definition: Double-precision 64-bit floating point type. The basic value space of double consists of the values m*2^e, where m is an integer whose absolute value is less than 2^53, and e is an integer between -1075 and 970, inclusive. In addition to the basic value space described above, the value space of double also contains the following three special values: positive and negative infinity and not-a-number (NaN). The special values positive and negative infinity and not-a-number have lexical representations INF, -INF and NaN, respectively. Lexical representations for zero may take a positive or negative sign. For example, -1E4, 1267.43233E12, 12.78e-2, 12 , -0, 0 and INF are all legal literals for double. A numeric datatype corresponding to the W3C XML Schema's xs:double datatype.

data.title: Count
data.definition: Ordinal number of objects in a finite set, discrete. A simple incrementing Integer type. When using in DDI-L, the "isSequence" facet must be set to true, and the "interval" facet must be set to "1".

data.title: Incremental
data.definition: A value that increases continuously and infinitely by a given amount. Use of this term in DDI-L indicates that the value increases by the amount provided in the "interval" facet; the "isSequence" facet will be set to "true".

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use if the numeric type is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: Fixed telephone
data.definition: A telephone that transmits signals converted from audio data through physical media, such as wire or fiber optic cable; also known as landline.

data.title: Fixed telephone: Personal/Private
data.definition: A fixed telephone belonging to a private person, usually located in a home or a private dwelling unit.

data.title: Fixed telephone: Organization/Business
data.definition: A fixed telephone of an organization, institution or business, or the work telephone of a person employed by the organization.

data.title: Mobile telephone
data.definition: A portable telephone connected to a wireless communications network through radio waves or satellite transmissions; includes phones known as cellular (or cell) phones, hand phones, as well as satellite phones.

data.title: Mobile telephone: Personal/Private
data.definition: A mobile telephone belonging to a private person.

data.title: Mobile telephone: Organization/Business
data.definition: A mobile telephone of an organization, institution or business, or the mobile work telephone of a person employed by the organization.

data.title: Fax
data.definition: A fax (short for facsimile) is a device used for the telephonic transmission of scanned-in printed material (text or images), usually to a telephone number associated with a printer or other output device; also known as telecopying.

data.title: Fax: Personal/Private
data.definition: A fax belonging to a private person.

data.title: Fax: Organization/Business
data.definition: The fax of an organization, institution or business, or the work fax of a person employed by the organization.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use when the type of telephone is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: Processing note
data.definition: A note related to the processing of the data, or metadata, or both.

data.title: Addendum
data.definition: Additional information, usually of a factual nature (as opposed to a comment), intended to clarify the content of a DDI section or module.

data.title: System note
data.definition: A note generated by the processing system used to produce the data, or metadata, or both.

data.title: Observation
data.definition: A note providing information on an aspect relevant for data usage that is likely to remain permanent, or a temporary note providing information for further review and correction. May be an observation entered by a human user or a system-generated note on any inconsistencies or deviations.

data.title: Comment
data.definition: A human-readable comment, typically of a more subjective nature than an addendum.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use when the type of note is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: Native
data.definition: The individual is a native user of the language whose level of proficiency is unknown/unspecified.

data.title: Native: Fluent
data.definition: The individual is a native user with excellent mastery of the language, including breadth of vocabulary and idiom, and confident command of the grammar.

data.title: Native: Good
data.definition: The individual is a native user of the language with good structural accuracy, vocabulary and comprehension.

data.title: Native: Basic
data.definition: The individual is a native user of the language with limited vocabulary, use of grammar and comprehension.

data.title: Non-native
data.definition: The individual is a non-native user of the language whose level of proficiency is unknown/unspecified.

data.title: Non-native: Fluent
data.definition: The individual is a non-native user with excellent mastery of the language, including breadth of vocabulary and idiom, and confident command of the grammar.

data.title: Non-native: Good
data.definition: The individual is a non-native user of the language with good structural accuracy, vocabulary and comprehension.

data.title: Non-native: Basic
data.definition: The individual is a non-native user of the language with limited vocabulary, use of grammar and comprehension.

data.title: Unspecified native status
data.definition: The individual's native status and her/his level of proficiency are both unknown, or not specified.

data.title: Unspecified native status: Fluent
data.definition: The individual's native status is unknown/unspecified; s/he has excellent mastery of the language, including breadth of vocabulary and idiom, and confident command of the grammar.

data.title: Unspecified native status: Good
data.definition: The individual's native status is unknown/unspecified; s/he has good structural accuracy, vocabulary and comprehension.

data.title: Unspecified native status: Basic
data.definition: The individual's native status is unknown/unspecified; s/he has limited vocabulary, use of grammar, and comprehension.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use if level of proficiency is known, but not found in the list. It is recommended that any new entry combine information about the individual's native/non-native status and his/her level of proficiency, following the format [native status].[proficiency level] as shown in the entries above.

data.title: Sum
data.definition: A value obtained as a result of adding two or more numbers (items/amounts).

data.title: Arithmetic mean
data.definition: Mathematical average of a set of values. The mean is calculated by adding up two or more values and dividing the total by their number. In social/political science, it is usually the sum of the measurements divided by the number of subjects, or cases.

data.title: Count
data.definition: Total number of units in a group of items.

data.title: Mode
data.definition: The value that appears most often in a set of values.

data.title: Median
data.definition: The middle value in a series of values arranged sequentially from smallest to largest.

data.title: Maximum
data.definition: The highest value attained or recorded.

data.title: Minimum
data.definition: The lowest value attained or recorded.

data.title: Percent
data.definition: The number of parts out of 100. In mathematics, a percentage is a number of ratio expressed as a fraction of 100. Percentages are used to express how large one quantity is relative to another quantity.

data.title: Cumulative percent
data.definition: The total of a frequency and all frequencies below it in a frequency distribution; the "running total" of frequencies [the maximum value is 100%].

data.title: Percentile rank
data.definition: The percentile rank of a item is the percentage of items in its frequency distribution which are lower [cannot reach 100%].

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use when the aggregation method is known, but not found in the list.

data.title: Self
data.definition: Unit of response is same as unit of observation/analysis.

data.title: Informant
data.definition: Unit of response is different than the unit of observation as part of the study design, and the identity of the response unit is also pre-determined by the study design. Such studies are actually called "informant surveys" and they involve, for instance, obtaining information about a community from certain select members who hold specific information, like church leaders, business owners or leaders, physicians, school teachers, civic leaders, etc. Or, if a business or organization is the unit of observation, information may be sought at different administrative/professional levels, etc.

data.title: Proxy
data.definition: Unit of response is different than the unit of analysis because the sampled unit is unavailable/unable to participate. Proxies may be allowed by the study design, but their identity is not specifically designated (for example, anyone in the household can provide information about another household member, or any available student can provide information about another student, etc.).

data.title: Interviewer
data.definition: Data are entered directly by the interviewer, as a result of his/her own observations, and not by eliciting answers to a question.

data.title: Other
data.definition: Use if the response unit is known, but not found in the list.
